he mother of a disabled child. A highly personal story of one family’s encounter with disability, Raising Henry is also an insightful exploration of today’s knotty terrain of social prejudice, disability policy, genetics, prenatal testing, medical training, and inclusive education. Adams untangles the contradictions of living in a society that is more enlightened and supportive of people with disabilities than ever before, yet is racing to perfect prenatal tests to prevent children like Henry from being born. Her book is gripping, beautifully written, and nearly impossible to put down. Once read, her family’s story is impossible to forget.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildren. 0aDevelopmentally disabled childrenzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aDown syndromexPatientszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aDown syndrome. 0aMother and child. 0aMothers and sonszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aParents of developmentally disabled childrenzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aParents. 0aPeople with mental disabilities. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030018000840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018429740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300184297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300184297/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY